text: This trailer seemed to show the whole movie. I hate trailers like this. Generally the reason why I don't watch trailers at all.    The things we **DO** know and watching the *trailer* tells us.    * It starts with character development and "immersive bonding", we'll see Brad "upvote" his father, meaning utmost resepect held. I can guarantee that Brad is likable in this movie as he's the protagonist the audience will bond with. His survival or at least actions matter to the audience.    * Brad has followed the footsteps of his father and is an astronaut on a mission on ISS (or similar space station) during which The Surge will occur. It's a huge thing, likely solar flare, but it could in theory also be an EMP caused by humans. Nothing indicates to that, so I'm going to bet on massive solar flare / celestial source.    * Brad falls and survives - how we don't know, but does it matter. He survives and recovers.    * Army is about to send Brad on a mission after his father whom got lost 16 years ago -> meaning Army has got some indication that something is going on out there.    * Wife worries about Brad before he's sent out to said Army mission.    * Mission prepares, Brad is good, but oh boy - the things he's about to experience during the mission.    * Scene on the Moon (or a massive barren asteroid) occurs, where we can see multiple vehicles and 10+ people.    * We're present around Saturn (rings) where EVA occurs. There's something that takes us to the Saturn. Accident or purposal?    * Another explosion occurs during the mission which Brad also narrowly escapes.    The things we **DO NOT** know and watching the *movie* will tell us:    * What causes The Surge?  * How does Brad survive The Surge?  * Why Brad's father was part of the E.T. mission 16 years ago?  * What did they find initially? What has been going on there all these years?  * Why does the <whatever happened out there> threat Earth and all other life?  * Why is there a plethora of people on the Moon/barren asteroid and there's fighting going on there?  * How do we get to Saturn and EVA there?  * Why is Brad chosen on this mission? Speculation: Related to his father -- knowledge of his father --> indicates father is alive and part of cause.  * Does Brad survive in the end of the movie? Does Earth survive? How about life? How does that happen?    Now the real question is:    Would you have rather watched this movie where you did not know the all the things the trailer revealed?

text: An incredibly boring, uncomplicated and uninspired drama film with space as a backdrop.    Spoiler alert: An emotionally distant guy goes looking for his emotionally distant father and ends up slightly less emotionally distant as a result. The only two things in this movie that had some depth was when it suggested that psychology only exists to turn humans into obedient slaves, but that could easily have been unintentional. And when his father says "we're a dying breed" which was only profound if you think about it in the context of them both being unconscious people which I'm sure was not the intention. It does try to imply that someone who did not care about life at all would sacrifice everything looking for life outside Earth and as such was really just searching for the life in himself which was not there. But it didn't come across very well and lacked any sort of impact.
